track_notes:
This is an easy drive-up, not far from I-20.  I was heading home on I-20 after a business trip to Birmingham.  You must stop at the ranger station/store and check in.  I told the ranger I was just going to drive to the tower site and make a few contacts with my radio.  I gave him a quick explanation of SOTA.  He was very accommodating.  There is a small fee that must be paid in cash.  I think it was $5 for a day pass.  This includes the key code to open the gate.  After you drive past the gate, continue up the paved road, called Bunker Loop.  You will see a two-story lodge on your left, which looks like a small hotel. Continue up Bunker Loop and take the first left.  This goes to the tower site.

I parked near the pavilion and walked down the hill to a clearing.  There are plenty of trees for a dipole.

When you finish the activation you cannot drive out the way you drove up.  The loop is one-way.  Bunker Loop circles back to the ranger station.  You could continue on the road you turn
